📝 Key Tags

  • <!DOCTYPE html> → Defines the HTML version (HTML5 in this case).

  • Inside <body>, we put visible stuff like headings and paragraphs.

📝 Key Tags & Usage

  • <h1> to <h6> → Headings, <h1> is biggest, <h6> smallest

  • <p> → Paragraph

  • <b> → Bold (not semantic, just style)

  • <strong> → Strong emphasis (semantic, also bold by default)

  • <i> → Italic (not semantic, just style)

  • <em> → Emphasis (semantic, italic by default)

  • <u> → Underline

  • <mark> → Highlight text

  • <small> → Smaller text

  • <sub> → Subscript (H₂O → the 2 is subscript)

  • <sup> → Superscript (x² → the 2 is superscript)

  • <br> → Line break

  • <hr> → Horizontal line

💻 Example Code Snippet

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Text Formatting Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Main Heading (h1)</h1>
    <h3>Sub Heading (h3)</h3>
    <p>This is a <b>bold</b> word and this is <strong>strong</strong>.</p>
    <p>This is <i>italic</i> and this is <em>emphasized</em>.</p>
    <p>This is <u>underlined</u> and this is <mark>highlighted</mark>.</p>
    <p>Water formula: H<sub>2</sub>O</p>
    <p>Math: x<sup>2</sup> + y<sup>2</sup></p>
    <p>Small text looks like <small>this text</small>.</p>
    <p>Line 1<br>Line 2 with a line break</p>
    <hr>
    <p>Paragraph after horizontal line</p>
</body>
</html>

📌 Explanation

  • Use <h1> to <h6> for headings (SEO and structure).

  • <b> and <i> are just styling, while <strong> and <em> add meaning for accessibility.

  • <mark>, <u>, <small>, <sub>, <sup> add special text effects.

  • <br> makes a new line, <hr> draws a divider line.

Alrighty 🚀 Let’s dig into Section 2: Text & Typography Tags — this one covers all the tags you’ll use to style and structure text, with both semantic (meaningful) and purely visual options.

📝 Key Tags & Purpose

  • Headings: <h1> … <h6> → Structured titles, <h1> = most important.

  • Paragraphs: <p> → Normal text block.

  • Bold/Strong: <b> (visual bold) vs <strong> (semantic emphasis, usually bold).

  • Italic/Emphasis: <i> (visual italics) vs <em> (semantic emphasis, usually italic).

  • Underline: <u> → Underlined text.

  • Highlight: <mark> → Yellow highlighted text.

  • Small text: <small> → Smaller size.

  • Subscript: <sub> (H₂O).

  • Superscript: <sup> (x²).

  • Line break: <br> → Single line break (not a new paragraph).

  • Horizontal rule: <hr> → A thematic divider line.

  • Delete/Insert: <del> (crossed-out) / <ins> (underlined addition).

  • Abbreviation: <abbr> with title → Tooltip on hover.

  • Quote: <q> (inline short quote), <blockquote> (longer quoted section).

  • Code/Preformatted: <code> (inline code) / <pre> (block of preformatted text).

  • Keyboard input: <kbd> → Shows key presses.

  • Sample output: <samp> → Example program output.

  • Citation: <cite> → Reference for a work.

  • Address: <address> → Contact or author info.

💻 Example Code Snippet

html

<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">

</head>
<body>
  <h1>Main Title (h1)</h1>
  <h3>Subsection (h3)</h3>
  <p>This is a normal paragraph.</p>
  
  <p><b>Bold</b> vs <strong>Strong</strong></p>
  <p><i>Italic</i> vs <em>Emphasized</em></p>
  <p><u>Underlined</u> and <mark>Highlighted</mark></p>
  
  <p>Water formula: H<sub>2</sub>O</p>
  <p>Math: E = mc<sup>2</sup></p>
  
  <p><small>Smaller note text.</small></p>
  <p>Line 1<br>Line 2 (with line break)</p>
  <hr>
  
  <p>Update: <del>Old Price $100</del> <ins>New Price $80</ins></p>
  <p>Hover abbreviation: <abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr></p>
  
  <blockquote>
    “This is a blockquote — for longer quotations.”
  </blockquote>
  <p>Inline quote: <q>Short quoted phrase</q></p>
  
  <p>Inline code: <code>console.log("Hello")</code></p>
  <pre>
function hello() {
  console.log("Preformatted code block");
}
  </pre>
  
  <p>Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd> to copy.</p>
  <p>Program output: <samp>Hello World</samp></p>
  <p><cite>The Art of Computer Programming</cite> by Donald Knuth</p>
  
  <address>
    Written by John Doe<br>
    Visit us at: example.com<br>
    City, Country
  </address>
</body>
</html>

📌 Explanation Highlights

  • Use semantic tags (<strong>, <em>, <cite>, <abbr>) for meaning; screen readers and SEO benefit.

  • <code>, <kbd>, <samp> give context in technical docs.

  • <address> is not for physical styling—it specifically indicates contact info.

  • <blockquote> vs <q>: block vs inline quoting.

📝 Section 2: Text & Typography — Detailed Explanations

1. <h1> … <h6> — Headings

  • Purpose: Defines headings from most important (<h1>) to least important (<h6>). Helps search engines & screen readers understand the document structure.

  • Attributes:

    • id: unique identifier (useful for linking with anchors).

    • class: apply CSS styles.

    • title: tooltip text when hovered.

    • lang: language of heading (e.g., lang="fr").

    • dir: text direction (ltr or rtl).

  • Example:

    html
    <h1 id="main-title" title="Main page heading">Main Heading</h1>
<h3 class="sub">Subheading</h3>

2. <p> — Paragraph

  • Purpose: Groups sentences into paragraphs. Creates space before/after automatically.

  • Attributes: Same as above (global attributes like id, class, title, etc.).

  • Example:

    html
    <p id="intro" class="lead">This is a paragraph of text.</p>

3. <b> vs <strong>

  • <b>: Makes text bold visually.

  • <strong>: Emphasizes importance — screen readers read it with stress. Use this for meaning.

  • Attributes: All global ones.

  • Example:

    html
    <p><b>Visual bold</b> vs <strong>Important text</strong></p>

4. <i> vs <em>

  • <i>: Italic, usually for names, foreign words, or terms.

  • <em>: Emphasized stress. Screen readers change tone.

  • Example:

    html
    <p><i>Italic style</i> vs <em>Emphasized meaning</em></p>

5. <u>, <mark>, <small>

  • <u>: Underlines text.

  • <mark>: Highlights text (like yellow marker).

  • <small>: Shows side comments, fine print, or disclaimers in smaller text.

  • Example:

    html
    <p><u>Underlined</u>, <mark>Highlighted</mark>, <small>fine print</small></p>

6. <sub> & <sup>

  • Purpose: Subscript (below line, e.g. H₂O) and superscript (above line, e.g. x²).

  • Example:

    html
    <p>Water: H<sub>2</sub>O — Math: x<sup>2</sup></p>

7. <br> & <hr>

  • <br>: Inserts a line break (new line). Use in addresses, poems.

  • <hr>: Horizontal line, thematic break between topics.

  • Attributes for <hr>:

    • role: defines meaning (e.g., role="separator").

    • aria-hidden: hide from screen readers if decorative.

  • Example:

    html
    Line 1<br>Line 2
<hr>

8. <del> & <ins>

  • Purpose: Mark deleted and inserted text (great for tracking edits or price changes).

  • Attributes:

    • datetime: when the change happened.

    • cite: link to source of change.

  • Example:

    html
    <p>Price: <del datetime="2024-08-01">₹1200</del> 
   <ins datetime="2024-09-01">₹950</ins></p>

9. <abbr>

  • Purpose: Short abbreviation, full form shown with tooltip.

  • Attributes:

    • title: expanded text (required for meaning).

    • aria-label: accessibility-friendly description.

  • Example:

    html
    <p><abbr title="Cascading Style Sheets">CSS</abbr></p>

10. <q> & <blockquote>

  • <q>: Inline short quotation (adds quotes automatically).

  • <blockquote>: Long block quotes.

  • Attributes:

    • cite: URL of source.

  • Example:

    html
    <q cite="https://example.com">Short quote</q>
<blockquote cite="https://example.com">
  This is a long quotation.
</blockquote>

11. <code> & <pre>

  • <code>: Inline code.

  • <pre>: Preformatted text (keeps spacing & newlines). Often used together.

  • Example:

    html
    <p>Use <code>console.log()</code> in JS</p>
<pre><code>function hello() {
  console.log("hi");
}</code></pre>

12. <kbd> & <samp>

  • <kbd>: User input from keyboard.

  • <samp>: Sample output from a program.

  • Example:

    html
    Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>C</kbd>
Output: <samp>Copied!</samp>

13. <cite> & <address>

  • <cite>: Reference to creative works (book, article, painting).

  • <address>: Contact/author info (not postal address only).

  • Example:

    html
    <cite>Learning HTML</cite>
<address>
  John Doe<br>
  <a href="mailto:john@example.com">john@example.com</a>
</address>

🔥 That’s the detailed breakdown with explanations for all Text & Typography tags.

🏗️ Section 1 — Document Structure

1. <!DOCTYPE html>

Tag explanation:

  • Declares document type.

  • Ensures browser uses HTML5 standard mode (not quirks mode).

Attributes:

  • None.

Attribute explanation:

  • N/A

Code snippet:

html

2. <html>

Tag explanation:

  • Root element that contains the entire document.

  • Must wrap <head> and <body>.

Attributes:

  • lang, dir, id, class, title, data-*

Attribute explanation:

  • lang: Document language (lang="en", lang="hi").

  • dir: Text direction (ltr = left-to-right, rtl = right-to-left).

  • id: Unique identifier for scripts/styles.

  • class: Grouping/styling purposes.

  • title: Tooltip when hovered.

  • data-*: Store custom data for scripts.

Code snippet:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>

    <title>HTML Tag Example</title>

  </body>
</html>

3. <head>

Tag explanation:

  • Contains metadata (information about the page).

  • Not displayed directly to users.

Attributes:

  • None (but accepts global attributes like id, class).

Attribute explanation:

  • Rarely used global attributes here; typically kept clean.

Code snippet:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Head Example</title>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
</head>
<body>
  <p>Head section contains metadata only.</p>
</body>
</html>

4. <title>

Tag explanation:

  • Defines the title of the page (shown on browser tab & in search engine results).

  • Must be inside <head>.

Attributes:

  • None (only global attributes like id, class).

Attribute explanation:

  • Not commonly needed; keep it simple.

Code snippet:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>My Awesome Page</title>
</head>
<body>
  <p>The title is visible on the browser tab.</p>
</body>
</html>

5. <body>

Tag explanation:

  • Contains all visible content of the page (headings, paragraphs, images, links, etc.).

  • Everything you see on a webpage lives inside <body>.

Attributes:

  • onload, onunload, id, class, title, style, data-*

Attribute explanation:

  • onload: Run script when page finishes loading.

  • onunload: Run script when page is closed.

  • style: Inline CSS styling.

  • id, class, title, data-*: General/global usage.

Code snippet:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Body Example</title>
</head>
<body onload="alert('Page loaded!')">
  <h1>Welcome!</h1>
  <p>This is content inside the body.</p>
</body>
</html>

📘 HTML Notes – Section 3: Links & Images

1. <a> (Anchor / Hyperlink)

Explanation: Used to create hyperlinks to other pages, files, locations in the same page, email, or phone numbers.
Attributes:

  • href: Destination URL.

  • target: Where to open the link (_blank, _self, _parent, _top, or frame name).

  • download: Prompts download of the linked file.

  • rel: Relationship of linked document (nofollow, noopener, noreferrer).

  • hreflang: Language of the linked resource.

  • type: MIME type of resource.

  • Global attributes.
    Code snippet:

html
<a href="https://example.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Visit Example</a>
<a href="notes.pdf" download="LectureNotes.pdf">Download Notes</a>
<a href="mailto:info@example.com">Email Us</a>
<a href="tel:+911234567890">Call Us</a>
<a href="#section2">Jump to Section 2</a>

2. <img> (Image)

Explanation: Embeds images in a page. Self-closing tag.
Attributes:

  • src: Image file path/URL.

  • alt: Alternative text for accessibility & SEO.

  • width / height: Dimensions (px or %).

  • loading: Lazy loading (lazy, eager).

  • srcset: Multiple image sources for responsive design.

  • sizes: Image display sizes depending on viewport.

  • crossorigin: For CORS handling.

  • referrerpolicy: How referrer info is sent.

  • Global attributes.
    Code snippet:

html
<img src="photo.jpg" alt="Beautiful Sunset" width="400" height="250">
<img src="icon.png" alt="App Icon" loading="lazy">
<img src="small.jpg" srcset="large.jpg 1024w, medium.jpg 640w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 480px, 800px" alt="Responsive Image">

3. <picture> (Responsive Images)

Explanation: Container for multiple <source> elements to define different images for different devices/resolutions. Falls back to <img>.
Attributes: Global attributes.
Child tags: <source> with attributes.
Code snippet:

html
<picture>
  <source srcset="photo-large.jpg" media="(min-width: 800px)">
  <source srcset="photo-medium.jpg" media="(min-width: 400px)">
  <img src="photo-small.jpg" alt="Scenic Landscape">
</picture>

4. <map> & <area> (Image Maps)

Explanation: Create clickable areas inside an image.

  • <map>: Defines map.

  • <area>: Defines clickable region.
    Attributes (map): name, Global.
    Attributes (area):

  • shape: Shape (rect, circle, poly).

  • coords: Coordinates of shape.

  • href: Destination URL.

  • alt: Alt text for area.

  • target: Where to open link.

  • Global attributes.
    Code snippet:

html
<img src="diagram.png" usemap="#workmap" alt="Office Layout">
<map name="workmap">
  <area shape="rect" coords="34,44,270,350" href="desk.html" alt="Desk">
  <area shape="circle" coords="450,150,60" href="meeting.html" alt="Meeting Room">
</map>

5. <figure> & <figcaption>

Explanation:

  • <figure>: Groups images/diagrams with captions.

  • <figcaption>: Provides caption for <figure>.
    Attributes: Global.
    Code snippet:

html
<figure>
  <img src="chart.png" alt="Sales Chart">
  <figcaption>Figure 1: Monthly Sales</figcaption>
</figure>

📘 HTML Notes – Section 6: Forms & Input Elements

1. <form>

Explanation: Container for all input elements. Used to collect user data.
Attributes:

  • action: URL where form data is sent

Explanation: Defines various types of input fields. Self-closing tag.

  • type: Text, password, email, number, checkbox, radio, file, date, submit, reset, button, etc.

  • placeholder: Hint text

  • required, readonly, disabled, checked (for checkbox/radio)

  • min, max, step (number/date inputs)

  • pattern: Regex for validation

  • autocomplete, autofocus

  • Global attributes
    Code snippet:

html

  • Global attributes

  <h1>Website Title</h1>
  <nav>
    <a href="#home">Home</a>
    <a href="#about">About</a>
  </nav>
</header>

2. <footer>

Explanation: Represents footer content for a page or section (author info, copyright, links).
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<footer>
  <p>&copy; 2025 MyWebsite. All rights reserved.</p>
  <a href="#contact">Contact Us</a>
</footer>

3. <nav>

Explanation: Represents a section of navigation links.
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="#services">Services</a></li>
    <li><a href="#contact">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>

4. <main>

Explanation: Main content of the page. Only one <main> per page; excludes headers, footers, navs, and sidebars.
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<main>
  <h2>About Our Company</h2>
  <p>We provide quality web development services.</p>
</main>

5. <section>

Explanation: Defines thematic sections of content (e.g., “About”, “Services”).
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<section id="services">
  <h2>Our Services</h2>
  <p>Web Development, UI/UX Design, SEO</p>
</section>

6. <article>

Explanation: Represents independent content like blog posts, news, or forum posts.
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<article>
  <h2>Blog Post Title</h2>
  <p>Published on: 09-09-2025</p>
  <p>Content of the blog post...</p>
</article>

7. <aside>

Explanation: Represents content indirectly related to main content (sidebars, ads, notes).
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<aside>
  <h3>Related Posts</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="#post1">Post 1</a></li>
    <li><a href="#post2">Post 2</a></li>
  </ul>
</aside>

8. <figure> & <figcaption>

Explanation: Group media with caption (already covered in Section 3 but included semantically).
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<figure>
  <img src="diagram.png" alt="Diagram Example">
  <figcaption>Figure 1: Example Diagram</figcaption>
</figure>

9. <mark> & <time>

Explanation:

  • <mark>: Highlights text.

  • <time>: Represents date/time. Can have datetime attribute.
    Attributes: Global, plus datetime for <time>
    Code snippet:

html
<p><mark>Important Note</mark></p>
<time datetime="2025-09-09">September 9, 2025</time>

10. <details> & <summary>

Explanation: Creates expandable/collapsible content. <summary> defines the visible title.
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<details>
  <summary>More Info</summary>
  <p>This text is revealed when clicked.</p>
</details>

11. <dialog>

Explanation: Defines a dialog box or popup. Can be modal or non-modal.
Attributes: open (boolean)
Code snippet:

html
<dialog open>
  <p>This is a dialog box.</p>
  <button onclick="this.parentElement.close()">Close</button>
</dialog>

Let’s dive in:

📘 HTML Notes – Section 9: Meta Tags & Head Elements

1. <title>

Explanation: Defines the title of the webpage (shown in browser tab and search engines).
Attributes: Global (rarely used)
Code snippet:

html
<title>My First Webpage</title>

2. <meta>

Explanation: Provides metadata (description, keywords, author, viewport, charset, etc.)
Attributes:

  • name: Type of metadata (description, keywords, author, viewport)

  • content: Value for the metadata

  • charset: Character encoding (like UTF-8)

  • http-equiv: HTTP headers (refresh, X-UA-Compatible)
    Code snippet:

html
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="description" content="Learn HTML basics">
<meta name="keywords" content="HTML, CSS, Web Development">
<meta name="author" content="John Doe">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<meta http-equiv="refresh" content="30">

3. <link>

Explanation: Links external resources like CSS files, icons, and prefetch.
Attributes:

  • rel: Relationship (stylesheet, icon, preload, prefetch)

  • href: URL of resource

  • type: MIME type (text/css, image/png)

  • media: Media type (screen, print)

  • Global attributes
    Code snippet:

html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
<link rel="icon" href="favicon.ico" type="image/x-icon">
<link rel="preload" href="script.js" as="script">

4. <style>

Explanation: Embeds internal CSS inside <head> or <body> (though <head> preferred).
Attributes:

  • type: CSS type (text/css)

  • media: Media type (screen, print)

  • Global attributes
    Code snippet:

html
<style>
  body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
  }
  h1 {
    color: #333;
  }
</style>

5. <script>

Explanation: Embeds JavaScript code or links external JS files.
Attributes:

  • src: External file URL

  • type: Script type (text/javascript)

  • async: Load script asynchronously

  • defer: Load after HTML parsing

  • crossorigin: For CORS-enabled scripts

  • Global attributes
    Code snippet:

html
<script>
  console.log("Hello, World!");
</script>

<script src="script.js" defer></script>

6. <base>

Explanation: Sets base URL for all relative links on the page. Only one <base> allowed.
Attributes:

  • href: Base URL

  • target: Default target for links (_blank, _self, etc.)
    Code snippet:

html
<base href="https://example.com/" target="_blank">
<a href="page.html">Go to Page</a> <!-- Opens https://example.com/page.html in new tab -->

7. <noscript>

Explanation: Content displayed if JavaScript is disabled.
Attributes: Global
Code snippet:

html
<noscript>
  <p>Please enable JavaScript to use this website.</p>
</noscript>

Let’s move on to Section 10: Deprecated & Obsolete Tags — tags you might see in old code but shouldn’t use in modern HTML.

📘 HTML Notes – Section 10: Deprecated & Obsolete Tags

1. <font>

Explanation: Used to set font size, color, and face. Deprecated in HTML5; use CSS instead.
Attributes:

  • color, face, size (all replaced by CSS)
    Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated way -->
<font color="red" size="4">Hello World</font>

<!-- Modern way -->
<span style="color:red; font-size:20px;">Hello World</span>

2. <center>

Explanation: Centers content horizontally. Deprecated; use CSS text-align: center.
Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<center><p>Centered Text</p></center>

<!-- Modern -->
<p style="text-align:center;">Centered Text</p>

3. <big> & <strike>

Explanation:

  • <big>: Makes text larger (use CSS font-size)

  • <strike>: Strikethrough text (use <del> or text-decoration: line-through)
    Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<big>Big Text</big>
<strike>Strikethrough</strike>

<!-- Modern -->
<span style="font-size:1.5em;">Big Text</span>
<span style="text-decoration:line-through;">Strikethrough</span>

4. <u> (Old meaning)

Explanation: Originally underlined text for stylistic purpose. Still valid in HTML5 but use <span> with CSS for styling meaningfully.
Code snippet:

html
<u>Old Underline</u> <!-- Valid but semantic CSS preferred -->
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Preferred</span>

5. <applet>

Explanation: Embedded Java applets. Obsolete; replaced by <object> or modern JS.
Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<applet code="HelloWorld.class" width="200" height="100"></applet>

<!-- Modern -->
<object data="HelloWorld.class" width="200" height="100"></object>

6. <acronym>

Explanation: Represents acronyms; replaced by <abbr> in HTML5.
Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<acronym title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</acronym>

<!-- Modern -->
<abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>

7. <frameset> & <frame>

Explanation: Divided browser window into multiple frames. Obsolete; replaced by <iframe> or CSS layouts.
Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<frameset cols="50%,50%">
  <frame src="left.html">
  <frame src="right.html">
</frameset>

<!-- Modern -->
<iframe src="left.html" width="50%" height="400"></iframe>
<iframe src="right.html" width="50%" height="400"></iframe>

8. <marquee>

Explanation: Creates scrolling text. Obsolete; use CSS animations.
Code snippet:

html
<!-- Deprecated -->
<marquee>Scrolling Text</marquee>

<!-- Modern -->
<div style="overflow:hidden; white-space:nowrap;">
  <span style="display:inline-block; animation: scroll 5s linear infinite;">Scrolling Text</span>
</div>
<style>
@keyframes scroll {
  0% { transform: translateX(100%); }
  100% { transform: translateX(-100%); }
}
</style>
